Airline Delay Prediction¶

MIGUEL PEREZ CARO¶

The idea is to receive on-time airline performance data and calculate the departure delay for any scheduled flight. Things to note:

  1. 12 months (07.2018 - 06.2019) are for training/validation and 2 months (07.2019 - 08.2019) for testing purposes.
  2. Flight is classified as delayed, when it is late 15 minutes or more.
  3. DepDelay is the target variable (Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual departure time. Early departures show negative numbers).
  4. Scheduled departure time of the flight is the last available moment for doing prediction.
  5. For modeling/analysis use a subset of 8 carriers, which are the most common in the dataset.
  6. Feel free to use any publicly available information/dataset for feature engineering.
  7. Dont forget about exploratory data analysis (at least 3 questions & answers).

As there isn't a huge number of features, an initial analysis can be done to get a general idea of each feature we have:

  • FL_DATE: is the date of the flight in the forma yyyy-mm-dd. Useful to sort the data and can be also useful to find some pattern for specific dates or months.

  • OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER: the carrier code. Can be interesting to gather the cancellations and delays per carrier.

  • OP_CARRIER_FL_NUM: the fligh number for carrier. Each combination of origin-dest for two airports, in both directions, has a unique flight number for each carrier.

  • ORIGIN: origin airport code.
  • DEST: destination airport code.

The flight number with the origin and the dest is redundant. It may be interesting to find out if there is any airport where the delays or the cancellations are more frequent.

  • CRS_DEP_TIME: CRS Departure Time (local time: hhmm)
  • DEP_TIME: Actual Departure Time (local time: hhmm)
  • DEP_DELAY: Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual departure time. Early departures show negative numbers.

The actual departure time is calculated with the CRS_DEP_TIME and the DEP_DELAY, so it's not necessary.

  • CRS_ARR_TIME: CRS Arrival Time (local time: hhmm)
  • ARR_TIME: Actual Arrival Time (local time: hhmm)
  • ARR_DELAY: Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual arrival time. Early arrivals show negative numbers.

Same situation as the previous one.

  • CANCELLED: Cancelled Flight Indicator (1=Yes)
  • CANCELLATION_CODE: Specifies The Reason For Cancellation

Analyze how the cancelation and delays are related.

  • CRS_ELAPSED_TIME: CRS Elapsed Time of Flight, in Minutes
  • ACTUAL_ELAPSED_TIME: Elapsed Time of Flight, in Minutes

Can be calculated with the departures and arrival times.

  • AIR_TIME: Flight Time, in Minutes
  • DISTANCE: Distance between airports (miles)

The air time and distance should be correlated. There may be cases that aren't and would point to an issue during the flight, probably outliers.

  • CARRIER_DELAY: Carrier Delay, in Minutes
  • WEATHER_DELAY: Weather Delay, in Minutes
  • NAS_DELAY: National Air System Delay, in Minutes
  • SECURITY_DELAY: Security Delay, in Minutes
  • LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY: Late Aircraft Delay, in Minutes

Analyze all of them.

  • As for all the times, there are some important points:

    • For the departure times, the actual departure can be delated. The scheduled time may be relevant and the departure delay is the target.
    • For the arrival time, since the idea is to work with on time data, the actual arrival and the arrival delay will not be known, so can be deleted.
    • The CRS elapsed time of flight can be known but the actual won't be known so can be deleted.
    • Air time, as I assume is calculated after the plane arrives, is not known neither.
    • Distance is known so is needed to analyze it.

  • The features CARRIER_DELAY, WEATHER_DELAY, NAS_DELAY, SECURITY_DELAY and LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY seem to be an explanation of the delay for the flight. My understanding is that the explanation of the delay isn't real time data for some of those features so in those cases, features shouldn't be used to predict the target variable. Some key points for flight delays are captured with those features:

    • Weather conditions: instead of using the feature WEATHER_DELAY, would be more realistic approach to use the current weather situation for the airport. As my understanding for this feature is that it's an explanation of how much time a flight was delayed due to weather conditions which is something unknown, this feature should be removed or modify to a categorical value that simply tell if there was a delay due to weather condition, classify it as 1.0 and if there wasn't as 0, which could be meaning that there was or not bas weather condition.
    • Airport congestion: this can be calculated in advanced based on the traffic in the airport and my understanding is that this delay is collected in the feature NAS_DELAY.
    • Security delay: the time involve in a security issue cannot be calculated in advanced, so for those cases, I believe that a more realistic approach is to collect if there was or not a security issue.
    • A previous flight delay: this is something that can be calculated based on the previous flight that should arrive to the destination which will be the origin of another fligh and is collected in the variable Late_Aircraft_Delay.
    • Other problems as mechanical issues, waiting for connecting passengers, waiting for crew, can be reasons why a flight is delayed, and may be collected in the feature CARRIER_DELAY, which would be an explanation of the delay so I think this is not known previously and this feature should be removed. More information could be collected for example with a feature Connecting_Passengers, to collect if there are connecitons for that plane, and the Delay_Connecting_Passenger, to collect if there is a delay on the previous plane of those passengers. A feature named Mechanical_Issue could be useful too, and maybe another for Strike, which is also a reason of flight delays.

Add a range for the departure time meaning that from 00:00 to 01:00 will be 0, from 01:00 to 02:00 will be 1 and so on

In [151]:
a = list(set(df_raw['CRS_DEP_TIME']))
In [152]:
def get_range_dates(date):
    
    if len(str(date))==1:
        date = '000'+str(date)
    elif len(str(date))==2:
        date = '00'+str(date)
    elif len(str(date))==3:
        date = '0'+str(date)
    else:
        date = str(date)
    date = int(date[:2])
    
    return date

df_raw['DEP_TIME'] = df_raw['CRS_DEP_TIME'].apply(lambda x: get_range_dates(x))
df_with_delays['DEP_TIME'] = df_with_delays['CRS_DEP_TIME'].apply(lambda x: get_range_dates(x))

def models_and_parameters_definition():
    """
    Auxiliary function to define the models to try and the grid parameter search for
    cross validation
    :return: dict of {'model':'gs_model'}
    """
    sgdr = Pipeline([('stds', StandardScaler()), ('sgdr', SGDRegressor())])
    params_sgdr = {'sgdr__alpha': [0.00001, 0.0001, 0.001]}
    gs_sgdr = GridSearchCV(sgdr,
                          params_sgdr,
                          cv=3,
                          scoring="neg_mean_squared_error",
                          verbose = 10)
    
    rf = RandomForestRegressor()
    params_rf = {'max_depth': [10, 30]} # Maximum number of levels in tree
    gs_rf = GridSearchCV(rf,
                         params_rf,
                         cv=3,
                         scoring="neg_mean_squared_error",
                         verbose = 10)


    dt = DecisionTreeRegressor()
    params_dt = {'max_depth': [10, 30, 50, 100]} # Maximum number of levels in tree
    gs_dt = GridSearchCV(dt,
                         params_dt,
                         cv=3,
                         scoring="neg_mean_squared_error",
                         verbose = 10)

    grid_search_models = {"gs_sgdr": gs_sgdr,
                          "gs_rf": gs_rf,
                          "gs_dt": gs_dt}
    return grid_search_models
In [180]:
def select_best_model(X_train, y_train, grid_search_models=False):
    """
    Function to select the best model with the best parameters
    :param grid_search_models: dictionary with all gridSearch we want to run. If it is not given to the function,
                              it runs models_and_parameters_definition function, where there are some models defined
    :param X_train: dataset of features to train the model
    :param y_train: categories to train the model
    :return:
    """
    if not grid_search_models:
        grid_search_models = models_and_parameters_definition()

    for name, grid_search in grid_search_models.items():
        print("Doing Grid Search of %s..." % name)
        grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

    best_score_each_gridsearch = [(model_name, grid_search.best_score_, grid_search.best_params_,
                                       str(grid_search.best_estimator_))
                                      for model_name, grid_search in grid_search_models.items()]
    
    df_best_score_each_gridsearch = pd.DataFrame(best_score_each_gridsearch,
                                                     columns=["gridSearchCV", "best_score", 
                                                              "best_params", "best_estimator"])
    
    df_sorted_best_score_each_gridsearch = (df_best_score_each_gridsearch.sort_values(by="best_score", 
                                                                                      ascending=False))
    

    
    model_summary = pd.DataFrame(df_sorted_best_score_each_gridsearch)
    best_model_name = model_summary['gridSearchCV'].values[0]
    best_model = grid_search_models.get(best_model_name)
    return best_model, model_summary, grid_search_models

Models can be trained and we will get the best model, the model summary which includes the parameters and score of the best model from each algorithm, and the estimator.

def model_performance_report(X, y, model):
    """
    Given a set of data and its labels returns a classification report
    :param X: dataset with features
    :param y: dataset with the label to classify
    :param model: classification model selected
    :return:
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y, y_pred)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y, y_pred)
    r2 = r2_score(y, y_pred)    
    return mae, mse, r2

def build_model():
    model = Sequential([
    Dense(500, activation='relu', input_shape=[X_train_dl.shape[1]]),
    Dense(100, activation='relu'),
    Dense(50, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1)])

    model.compile(loss='mse',
                  optimizer='adam',
                  metrics=['mae', 'mse'])
    return model

Conclusion¶

First of all, the performance for deep learning and the Random Forest is very similar, although the deep learning tehcnique could be modified to get better results with a better optimization but would take much more time.

The prediction could also be improved by:

  • Collecting weather data for every record.
  • Collecting the air traffic data for every record.
  • Adding other relevant features as, for example, if there are passengers connecting from a previous flight.
  • Getting data from every month so both month are weekday can be more relevant for the prediction and the bank holidays as New Year or Christmas can be also added.
